    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nI believe there was a mistake made when Neovim was updated to recognize systemd/Podman quadlet files in #37208.\n\nI am the original contributor to the Vim repo fix/commit. When I added the file recognition to `runtime/filetype.vim`, the line:\n\n```vim-script\nau BufNewFile,BufRead */containers/systemd/*.{artifact,build,container,image,kube,network,pod,volume}\tsetf systemd\n``` \nuses wildcards (`*`) to capture both the **parent** and child sides of the path.\n\nUsing the reference [podman-systemd.unit.5](https://docs.podman.io/en/latest/markdown/podman-systemd.unit.5.html), this parent wildcard should capture the following paths for the \"rootful\" units and a couple of the \"rootless\" units:\n\n- `/run/containers/systemd/`\n- `/etc/containers/systemd/`\n- `/usr/share/containers/systemd/`\n- `$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/containers/systemd/`\n- `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/containers/systemd/` or `~/.config/containers/systemd/`\n\nLooking at what was added in #37208 by @zeertzjq to `runtime/lua/vim/filetype.lua` (and using the line numbers in that pull for reference), it appears that lines 2378-2385 do not have the wildcard for the parent directory. I fully admit that I may be misunderstanding how the code works here and maybe the wildcard portion happens somewhere else?\n\nHowever, to support why I don't think the parent wildcard is happening, I finally got around to updating a container file (`~/.config/containers/systemd/ollama-service.container`) today and noticed that Neovim wasn't recognizing the file as `systemd` so my lsp isn't formatting/coloring the file. I confirmed this using `:set filetype?` which returns `filetype=`.\n\nWhen opening the file with Vim, the file has colors and running `set filetype?` returns `filetype=systemd` as expected.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nCreate a file `~/.config/containers/systemd/test.container`\n\nPut the following in the file:\n```\n[Unit]\nDescription=Test\n```\n\nOpen file with Neovim. Note if any formatting/coloring is occurring. Run `:set filetype?` and it should return `filetype=`\n\nOpen file with Vim. Note any formatting/coloring is occurring. Run `:set filetype?` and it should return `filetype=systemd`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nReferencing the \"Steps to reproduce\":\nWhen opening the file with Neovim, running `set filetype?` should return `filetype=systemd`\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.7\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim 9.2.283\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux 6.19.10-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nalacritty 0.16.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nArch repo using pacman package manager",
